A rational number can be expressed as a  fraction $\dfrac{a}{b}$, where both $a$ and $b$ are integers. In contrast, an **irrational number** cannot be expressed as a fraction $\dfrac{a}{b}$, where $a$ and $b$ are integers.

Remember that any integer can be represented as a fraction.  For example, $6=\dfrac61$.

We can substitute the numeric choices into the cube root expression and determine which result in an irrational number.

Choice (A): 

$\begin{align}
\sqrt[3]{(64-0)}&=\sqrt[3]{64}\\\\
&=\sqrt[3]{4\times4\times4}\\\\
&=\redD{4}
\end{align}$

Choice (B):

$\begin{align}
\sqrt[3]{(64-27)}&=\sqrt[3]{37} \\\\
&\approx\greenD{3.332} 
\end{align}$

Choice (C):

$\begin{align}
\sqrt[3]{(64-37)}&=\sqrt[3]{27}\\\\
&=\sqrt[3]{3\times3\times3}\\\\
&=\redD{3}
\end{align}$

Choice (D):

$\begin{align}
\sqrt[3]{(64-64)} &= \sqrt[3]{0} \\\\
&=\redD{0} 
\end{align}$

Choice (E):

$\begin{align}
\sqrt[3]{(64-91)}&=\sqrt[3]{-27}\\\\
&=\sqrt[3]{-3\times-3\times-3}\\\\
&=\redD{-3}
\end{align}$


Of the choices provided, only $27$ produces an irrational result.

**When  $x=27$,  the expression $\sqrt[3]{(64-x)}$ is an irrational number.**

We can distribute and combine like terms to determine which choice matches the expression given, $21-6x$.

$\begin{align}
5-2(8-3x)&=5-2(8)-2(-3x) \\\\
&=5-16+6x \\\\
&=\redD{-11+6x}
\end{align}$

$\begin{align}
6+3(5-2x)&=6+3(5)+3(-2x) \\\\
&=6+15-6x \\\\
&=\greenD{21-6x}
\end{align}$

$\begin{align}
25-(4-6x)&=25-1(4)-1(-6x)\\\\
&=25-4+6x \\\\
&=\redD{21+6x}
\end{align}$

$\begin{align}
3(4-2x)-9&=3(4)+3(-2x)-9 \\\\
&=12-6x-9 \\\\
&=\redD{3-6x}
\end{align}$

$\begin{align}
7(3-2x)-8x&=7(3)+7(-2x)-8x \\\\
&=21-14x-8x \\\\
&=\redD{21-22x}
\end{align}$

**$6+3(5-2x)$ is equivalent to $21-6x$.**

